r 40 new readings, including two all-new chapters on the Harper Conservatives and Aboriginal Law. Addressing current controversies, including the Canadian Judicial Council’s investigations into Justice Robin Camp and Lori Douglas and the Trudeau Government’s re-introduction of the Court Challenges Program, this book strives for competing perspectives, with many readings juxtaposed to foster debate. Taking a critical approach to the Charter of Rights and Freedoms and the growth of judicial power, editors F.L. Morton and Dave Snow provide an even-handed examination of current and ongoing issues. Law, Politics, and the Judicial Process in Canada, 4th Edition is the leading source for students interested in the Charter of Rights and Freedoms and the growth of judicial power in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCourtszCanada. 0aCourts-Canada. 0aJudicial processzCanada. 0aJudicial process-Canada. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzCanada. 7aLAW / Courts.2bisacsh  aAboriginal law.  aCanadian judicial system.  aCanadian judiciaty.  aCanadian law.  aCharter of Rights and Freedoms.  aCourt Challenges Program.  aHarper conservatives.  aIndigenous law.  aJustice Robin Camp.  aLori Douglass.  aRobin Camp.  aTrudeau Government.  ainterest groups.  ajudicial access.  ajudicial decision making.  ajudicial ethics.  ajudicial independence.  ajudicial recruitment.  ajudicial review.  ajudicial selection.  alegal reasoning.  aprecidents.1 aMorton, F.L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSnow, Dave, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z9783111275